  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 하삭(河朔) 지방 : '
    value: 하는 황하(黃河)이고, 삭(朔)은 북쪽의 의미이니, 하삭지민(河朔之民)은 곧 황하 이북 지역의 민중을 말하는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 기각지세(掎角之勢) : '
    value: 의각지세(犄角之勢)라고도 한다. 사슴을 잡을 때에, 한사람은 뒷발을 얽어매고 한사람은 뿔을 붙잡는다는 말에서 유래한 것으로, 전쟁할 때에 ‘기각지세’ 를 이룬다는 것은 양쪽으로 포진하여 적을 제어하는 형세를 말하는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 녹각원(鹿角垣) : '
    value: 대나 목재를 엮되 가지를 사슴뿔처럼 밖으로 향하게 하여 적병의 접근에 대비하는 방어 시설을 녹시(鹿柒)ㆍ녹채(鹿寨)ㆍ녹채(鹿砦)ㆍ녹각채(鹿角砦) 등으로 이름한다. ‘녹각원’은 담장을 쌓고 그러한 시설을 한 것을 말함이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 부월(斧鉞) : '
    value: 큰 도끼로. 옛날에 장군이 출정할 때 그의 위신을 세워주기 위하여 천자(天子)가 하사하던 것.
english:
  title: Record of General Kim Pyeong's Military Campaign
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The general's name was Jiryeo, later changed to Jiru. He was from Eonyang County in Gyerim. In his youth, through his father's merit, he rose to the rank of Jeonguii and was selected for the Eastern Palace Guard. He was promoted to Junglang-jang and commanded the Yurim forces. Within a few years, he was elevated to general and stationed at the northeastern frontier, where the Khitans and Jurchens dared not venture. For his service, he was appointed Great General of the Cheonuwei Guard.

    In the second year of King Kang's reign, on a cycle day of Gyeyu, he toured and pacified the frontier. The border people both feared and loved him. In the third year of King Go's reign, in the eighth lunar month of a Byungja year, the Khitans invaded our borders. The commander of the northwestern frontier reported by letter, arriving on the twelfth day of that month. The king appointed General No Won-sun as commander of the central army, O Eung-bu as commander of the right army, and the general as acting supreme general commanding the rear guard.

    On the thirteenth day, a great military review was held at Sunchen Pavilion. On the twenty-second day, the right army was positioned at Seobo, the central army at Lukyo, and the rear guard at Gwajeon. After two nights, they departed.

    Long ago, when the Yuan Emperor Sengmu first attacked the Khitan capital of Yanjing, the Jin Dynasty's Emperor Xuanzong fled to Bian. After Sengmu withdrew northward, leaving garrison forces in Yanjing, the people of Yanjing feasted the soldiers and slaughtered them in their drunkenness. The remnant Khitans—the sons of King Kimsan and King Kimsi—appointed the brigand Aer-qinnu as their general and coerced the people of the Yellow River region into submission, declaring themselves the Recovered Kingdom of the Great Liao. Sengmu was enraged and launched a great campaign against them. The two kings swept eastward and requested land and provisions from us, which we refused. Already harboring designs on our kingdom, they used this as an excuse. Aer-qinnu led tens of thousands across the river with his families in tow, passing through Jinrong and Nyeongsaek toward Asacheon.

    Our three armies reached Joyang Fortress. The central army positioned itself within the city walls; the right and rear guards camped outside. When Joyang scouts reported the enemy's approach, all three armies selected elite troops for defense. Commander Wu Eung-yu and Divine Cavalry General Jeong Sun-u alone cut down over eighty enemy heads and captured more than twenty prisoners, seizing hundreds of livestock and numerous seals, weapons, and insignia. Wu Eung-yu led thirty-five hundred foot soldiers and encountered the enemy at Guiju's Direct Peak Village, slaying two hundred and capturing thirty-five. General Lee Yang-sung also routed the enemy at Changhung Station—all subordinates of the general.

    The three armies dispatched Divine Cavalry to pursue the enemy, engaging them at Sinri where seven hundred were slain. Advancing to Yeonzhou, the general stationed six commanders—Gwang-yu, Yeon-su, Zhou Min, Gwang-se, Gun-je, and Joha—at Lion's Peak, and three others—Young-rin, Jeok-bu, and Mun-bi—at Yang Valley.

    On the twenty-fifth day of the ninth month, these nine generals beheaded seven hundred enemy soldiers and captured countless horses, mules, oxen, insignia, and weapons. The enemy dared not divide their forces further but gathered at Gaebyeong Station. Though our three armies arrived, all hesitated to advance. The right army held the southern slope; the central army stood exposed in the field and withdrew slightly to Doksan. The general drew his sword, spurred his horse, and together with Commander Gi Jon-jeong directly pierced the enemy encirclement, charging forth with unstoppable fury. The enemy broke and fled beyond Gaebyeong. Setting an ambush north of the station, they suddenly attacked the central army, but the general wheeled about and routed them again.

    That night, General No told him: "Their numbers far exceed ours, and the right army has not arrived. We carried only three days' provisions, now exhausted. Better we retreat to Yeonzhou and await reinforcements." The general replied: "Our army has won successive victories, and our fighting spirit remains sharp. Let us press the advantage and settle this in one more battle."

    The enemy deployed across Muksang Field in great formation. General No sent riders calling the general while raising black banners as signal. The soldiers, ignoring the rain of blades, surged forward, each meeting a hundred foes. The general, with Commander Mun-bi, cut through the enemy ranks with irresistible force. After three engagements, three victories—yet the general's eldest son fell in the fray.

    Pursuing the routed enemy to South River of Hyangsan, thousands drowned in the waters. Women and children wailed together like ten thousand oxen lowing. One man cast down his weapons, declaring himself an official, and stepped forward pleading: "We have troubled your kingdom's borders, and our guilt is certain. But these women and children—what do they know of war? Spare them, and we shall return on the appointed day."

    The general sent word: "How can we trust your promise?" He gave the man wine, and the man drank deeply and departed.

    Soon Aer-qinnu sent documents imploring mercy, speaking as he had promised. Our three armies each dispatched two thousand men to pursue. The enemy abandoned provisions, weapons, and animals along the way—some cattle were hamstrung, others pierced—rendered useless that we might not benefit from them. Six thousand soldiers engaged at Cheongsae Fortress, capturing and slaying many. When the enemy finally crossed Cheongsae and escaped, they fled northeastward.

    Months later, when the enemy regrouped with Jurchen allies and pressed forward once more, in a valley called Yeosu, fighting resumed. Starving and fevered, the general refused to retreat. "Better to become a ghost of the frontier," he declared, "than to abandon my post for comfort." When waters and food could not pass his lips, when his eyes could not discern men from objects, an imperial command came ordering him to the capital for healing.

    Recorder Hong Chang-yeon and General Lee Jung-lip carried him on a litter to the city, where after months he recovered. In his absence, the enemy broke dozens of cities, trampling through empty lands.

    When a new commander was appointed, the general again marched. At Gaebyeong, Muksang, Hyangsan—in each engagement the rear guard led the van, the few striking down the many, protecting the weak so they might live.

    The general held discipline stern—no soldier dared molest the people. When wine arrived, he would drink first from a great cup, then share equally with the lowest-ranked men, earning their devotion unto death. After victory, he never claimed credit alone but always conferred with other commanders, submitting their names jointly, never boasting of his own abilities.

    Then came the night assault at Heunggyo Station, battles at Hongbeop Temple and beyond. Each time our forces prevailed. Yet in winter's bitter freeze, the enemy crossed Cheoncheon and slipped away westward into the mountains.

    A new marshal was appointed. After defeats and victories, through councils of war and nights under stars, the general's wisdom and valor shone. When Yuan generals arrived demanding aid and provisions, when lesser commanders hesitated, the general said: "The fate of the realm hangs in this moment. To refuse would be fatal." He went forth as emissary and envoy.

    The general stood six feet five inches tall, his beard flowing past his waist. When Yuan General Hazhen beheld him and heard his words—especially his refusal to bow to false emperors—great wonder seized him. "Come, sit as my elder brother," he declared. Through shared meals, through trials of courtesy and strength, the general won honor for the kingdom.

    When the traitor's city at last fell, when the rebel king took his own life, the general and the Yuan general exchanged oaths of eternal brotherhood. Hazhen returned gifts—captive women and livestock—and spoke words of respect.

    After returning home, the general continued to serve with the same steadfastness. When lesser nobles plotted rebellion, he crushed them with mercy, executing only the ringleaders and sparing the misled. The northern frontier found peace.

    In his later years, the general rose to become prime minister under King Go, holding the position of Grand Secretariat for eight years. His deeds are recorded in the official histories. This record preserves merely five years of his military campaigns.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Yellow River region (河朔) refers to the territories north of the Yellow River, a strategic area often contested in frontier conflicts.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'pincer formation' (掎角之勢) is a tactical disposition where forces position themselves on two sides to encircle and control an enemy, derived from the hunting metaphor of holding a deer by its legs and antlers.
  - key: ''
    value: Deer-horn palisades (鹿角垣) were defensive fortifications constructed with branches or timber arranged outward like deer antlers to impede enemy approach.
  - key: ''
    value: The ceremonial axe (斧鉞) was traditionally bestowed upon generals by the emperor upon their departure for campaign, serving as a symbol of authority and imperial commission.
